Installing Eggdrop (devinkbrown fork)

This is the quick install guide; if you have had little or no experience
with UNIX or Eggdrop, READ THE README FILE NOW! This file is best for
experienced users.

NOTE: This fork uses Meson + Ninja. The traditional autoconf/make build
system used by upstream Eggdrop is not present here.

DEPENDENCIES
============

  Required on all platforms:
    - Tcl >= 8.6 development headers
    - Meson  >= 0.57.0
    - Ninja  (any recent version)

  Optional (auto-detected; enable/disable with meson -D flags):
    - OpenSSL >= 1.0  (libssl-dev)      TLS/SSL support
    - Python  >= 3.8  development       Python scripting module
    - zlib             development       compress module
    - liburing                           io_uring backend (Linux >= 5.1 only)

  Meson discovers dependencies via pkg-config first, then CMake, then a
  manual library search.  Make sure the relevant pkg-config .pc files are
  on PKG_CONFIG_PATH before running meson setup.

  ---- Debian / Ubuntu -------------------------------------------------------

    # Required
    sudo apt-get install meson ninja-build tcl-dev

    # Optional (install whichever you want)
    sudo apt-get install libssl-dev python3-dev zlib1g-dev liburing-dev

  ---- Fedora / RHEL / Rocky -------------------------------------------------

    # Required
    sudo dnf install meson ninja-build tcl-devel

    # Optional
    sudo dnf install openssl-devel python3-devel zlib-devel liburing-devel

  ---- macOS (Homebrew) -------------------------------------------------------

    # Required
    brew install meson ninja tcl-tk

    # Optional
    brew install openssl@3 python@3.12 zlib

    # Make Homebrew packages visible to pkg-config
    export PKG_CONFIG_PATH="$(brew --prefix openssl@3)/lib/pkgconfig:\
$(brew --prefix tcl-tk)/lib/pkgconfig:$PKG_CONFIG_PATH"

  ---- Windows: MSYS2 / MinGW-w64 --------------------------------------------

    Open the "UCRT64" MSYS2 shell.

    # Required
    pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-meson \
              mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-ninja \
              mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-tcl

    # Optional
    pacman -S mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-openssl \
              mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-python \
              mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-zlib

    Winsock2 and MsWSock (needed for the IOCP backend) ship with the
    Windows SDK and are linked automatically -- no extra package needed.

  ---- Windows: MSVC (Visual Studio 2019 or later) ---------------------------

    Step 1 — Install Visual Studio
      Install Visual Studio 2022 (Community edition is free) with the
      "Desktop development with C++" workload, or use the standalone
      Build Tools:
        https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/downloads/#build-tools-for-visual-studio-2022

    Step 2 — Install Meson and Ninja
      From a normal Command Prompt (not a developer prompt):

          pip install meson ninja

      Or download the Meson MSI from https://github.com/mesonbuild/meson/releases

    Step 3 — Install vcpkg and all dependencies
      vcpkg is Microsoft's open-source package manager for C/C++ libraries.

          git clone https://github.com/microsoft/vcpkg C:\vcpkg
          C:\vcpkg\bootstrap-vcpkg.bat

      Then install required and optional packages (all in one command):

          C:\vcpkg\vcpkg install ^
              tcl:x64-windows ^
              openssl:x64-windows ^
              zlib:x64-windows ^
              python3:x64-windows

      Winsock2 (ws2_32.lib) and MsWSock (mswsock.lib) are part of the
      Windows SDK included with Visual Studio -- no vcpkg package needed.

    Step 4 — Open an x64 developer prompt
      Start > "x64 Native Tools Command Prompt for VS 2022"
      This puts cl.exe, link.exe, and the Windows SDK on PATH.

    Step 5 — Point pkg-config at vcpkg output
      vcpkg installs pkg-config .pc files alongside each library.
      Set PKG_CONFIG_PATH so Meson finds them:

          set VCPKG=C:\vcpkg\installed\x64-windows
          set PKG_CONFIG_PATH=%VCPKG%\lib\pkgconfig
          set PATH=%VCPKG%\bin;%VCPKG%\tools\pkgconf;%PATH%

      (vcpkg installs pkgconf.exe automatically when you install any
      library that provides a .pc file.)

    Step 6 — Configure and build

          meson setup build/ --vsenv
          ninja -j%NUMBER_OF_PROCESSORS% -C build/

      --vsenv tells Meson to activate the MSVC environment automatically
      even if you forgot to open a developer prompt in step 4.

  ---- Cygwin -----------------------------------------------------------------

    Cygwin is a POSIX emulation layer; it does not expose Win32 IOCP APIs,
    so it compiles on the plain POSIX path using select() as its I/O
    backend.  Install via the Cygwin setup tool:

        Interpreters: tcl, tcl-devel
        Net:          openssl, libssl-devel
        Devel:        meson, gcc-core, git, ninja, python3-devel, zlib-devel

QUICK STARTUP
=============

1.  Configure the build directory:

        meson setup build/

    Common options:

        meson setup build/ -Dipv6=true -Dtls=enabled -Dpython=auto

    To see all available options:

        meson configure

2.  Compile using all available CPU cores:

    Linux / Cygwin:

        ninja -j$(nproc) -C build/

    macOS:

        ninja -j$(sysctl -n hw.logicalcpu) -C build/

    Windows (MSYS2 shell or MSVC developer prompt):

        ninja -j%NUMBER_OF_PROCESSORS% -C build/

3.  Install (default prefix /usr/local; set at configure time with --prefix):

        meson setup build/ --prefix=$HOME/eggdrop
        ninja -C build/ install

    To install to a different path after configure:

        meson install -C build/ --destdir /path/to/install

4.  Since version 1.8, Eggdrop can use SSL to protect botnet links.
    Generate SSL certificates after installing. See doc/TLS for details.

[The following steps are performed in the directory you installed Eggdrop into]

5.  Create your configuration file.

    OPTION A — interactive wizard (recommended):

        ./eggdrop --setup mybot.toml

      Answer a handful of questions; the wizard writes a complete TOML
      config for you. No Tcl knowledge needed, no chmod required.

    OPTION B — copy and edit the sample TOML file:

        cp eggdrop-basic.toml mybot.toml
        $EDITOR mybot.toml

      At minimum, set your nick, IRC servers, and owner handle.
      See eggdrop.toml for the full reference with every setting
      documented. The format is straightforward key = "value" pairs
      organised into sections like [bot], [servers], [channels].

    OPTION C — migrate an existing .conf to TOML:

        python3 scripts/conf2toml.py mybot.conf mybot.toml

      The .conf files are no longer installed, but the bot still loads
      them when passed on the command line (the Tcl parser is used
      automatically for any file without a .toml extension). This
      allows a zero-downtime migration.

6.  Start the bot with the "-m" option to create a user file:

        ./eggdrop -m mybot.toml

    Note: No 'chmod u+x' is needed for TOML configs. The bot reads the
    file directly; it is not executed as a shell script.

7.  When starting the bot in the future, simply drop the "-m":

        ./eggdrop mybot.toml

    That's it. No need to make the file executable or add a shebang line.

8.  Run your bot via systemd or crontab so it restarts automatically:

    systemd:

        ./scripts/autobotchk mybot.toml -systemd

    crontab:

        ./scripts/autobotchk mybot.toml

9.  Smile. You have an Eggdrop!

I/O BACKENDS
============

  The build system automatically selects the best available backend:

    Platform             Backend    Notes
    -------------------- ---------- -----------------------------------------
    Linux >= 5.1         io_uring   liburing required; optional SQPOLL mode
    Linux                epoll      Persistent kernel interest set
    macOS / BSD          kqueue     Persistent kernel interest set
    Windows native       IOCP       Zero-byte overlapped WSARecv/WSASend
    Cygwin / fallback    select()   Portable; fd_set rebuilt each iteration

DEBUG BUILDS
============

      meson setup build/ -Degg-debug=true
      ninja -C build/

MODULES
=======

  Every module is built by default. Disable individually at configure time:

      meson setup build/ -Dmodule-compress=false -Dmodule-python=false

  List all module options:

      meson configure build/

This is the end. If you read to this point, hopefully you have also read
the README file. If not, then READ IT!

Have fun with Eggdrop!

